articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: U.S. consumer confidence fell for a second straight month in September amid worries about higher prices and the political environment, a survey showed on Tuesday.
articles.title: US consumer confidence ebbs in September

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: The United States has added three Chinese companies to the forced labor entity list involving Uyghurs, according to a government posting on Tuesday, as part of an effort to eliminate forced labor practices the U.S. supply chain.
articles.title: US adds three Chinese companies to forced labor entity list involving Uyghurs

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: U.S. Federal Communications Commission chair Jessica Rosenworcel on Tuesday said she would move quickly to reinstate landmark net neutrality rules rescinded under former President Donald Trump.
articles.title: US FCC chair proposes to restore net neutrality rules

articles.author: Lewis Krauskopf, Ankika Biswas, Shashwat Chauhan
articles.description: Wall Street's main indexes sank over 1% on Tuesday as 10-year Treasury yields held their multi-year highs, with investors still wrestling with prospects for a long period of high interest rates and the economic fallout.
articles.title: Wall St slides over 1% as Treasury yields hover at 16-year peaks

articles.author: Howard Schneider
articles.description: U.S. Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell said emphatically last week that people "hate inflation, hate it," but he left another fact unspoken - they also punish the politicians in charge when prices rise.
articles.title: The elusive Fed 'soft landing' nears. Why are Americans so mad about the economy?

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Volkswagen (VOWG_p.DE) will suspend production of ID.3 and Cupra Born electric cars at its Zwickau and Dresden plants in Germany in the first two weeks of October due to weaker demand, a spokesperson for the carmaker said on Tuesday.
articles.title: Volkswagen to temporarily cut production of two EV models due to weaker demand -spokesperson

articles.author: Jeff Mason, Nandita Bose
articles.description: President Joe Biden on Tuesday joined a picket line with striking autoworkers in Michigan, backing their call for a 40% pay raise and telling them they deserve a "lot more" than they are getting.
articles.title: Biden backs 40% UAW pay raise in Michigan strike visit

articles.author: Diane Bartz
articles.description: The U.S. Federal Trade Commission filed a long awaited antitrust lawsuit against Amazon.com on Tuesday, and asked the court to consider forcing the online retailer to sell assets as the government pressed on with its fight to rein in Big Tech's domination of the internet.
articles.title: US sues Amazon.com in landmark monopoly case after four-year probe

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Viktor Sokolov, the commander of Russia's Black Sea Fleet and one of Russia's most senior navy officers, was shown on Tuesday attending a video conference, a day after Ukrainian special forces said they had killed him.
articles.title: Russian Black Sea commander shown working after Ukraine said it killed him
